We should just log a warning if it is specified.","state":"OPEN","user":{"login":"JoshLove-msft"},"labels":["Client","EngSys"],"created_at":"2026-03-20T17:48:06Z","updated_at":"2026-03-20T18:56:49Z"},{"number":57303,"title":"The generated code should use ToSerialString() to construct a request","body":"When serializing an enum to a string, the generated code should call ToSerialString.
However, when an enum is used as a path parameter (for example, as shown below):

``` js
/**
 * Regenerates either the primary or secondary admin API key. You can only regenerate one key at a time.
 */
#suppress &#34;@azure-tools/typespec-azure-resource-manager/arm-resource-operation&#34; &#34;FIXME: Update justification, follow aka.ms/tsp/conversion-fix for details&#34;
@autoRoute
@post
op privateLinkResourcesRegenerateCustomization(
  ...ApiVersionParameter,
  ...SubscriptionIdParameter,
  ...CommonTypes.ResourceGroupNameParameter,

  /** The name of the Azure AI Search service associated with the specified resource group. */
  @path
  @segment(&#34;searchServices&#34;)
  @key
  @pattern(&#34;^(?=.{2,60}$)[a-z0-9][a-z0-9]+(-[a-z0-9]+)*$&#34;)
  searchServiceName: string,

  /**
   * Specifies which key to regenerate. Valid values include &#39;primary&#39; and &#39;secondary&#39;.
   */
  @path
  keyKind: AdminKeyKind,

  #suppress &#34;@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core/documentation-required&#34; &#34;FIXME: Update justification, follow aka.ms/tsp/conversion-fix for details&#34;
  body: void,
  #suppress &#34;@azure-tools/typespec-azure-core/documentation-required&#34; &#34;FIXME: Update justification, follow aka.ms/tsp/conversion-fix for details&#34;
  params?: `search-management-request-options`,
): ArmResponse | CloudError;
```

The generated code currently uses ToString() instead of ToSerialString() when constructing the request.
For example, the generated code for the definition above is:

``` .net
        public virtual Response RegenerateAdminKey(SearchServiceAdminKeyKind keyKind, SearchManagementRequestOptions searchManagementRequestOptions = default, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        {
            using DiagnosticScope scope = _adminKeysClientDiagnostics.CreateScope(&#34;SearchServiceResource.RegenerateAdminKey&#34;);
            scope.Start();
            try
            {
                RequestContext context = new RequestContext
                {
                    CancellationToken = cancellationToken
                };
                HttpMessage message = _adminKeysRestClient.CreateRegenerateAdminKeyRequest(Guid.Parse(Id.SubscriptionId), Id.ResourceGroupName, Id.Name, keyKind.ToString(), default, context);
                Response result = Pipeline.ProcessMessage(message, context);
                Response response = Response.FromValue(SearchServiceAdminKeyResult.FromResponse(result), result);
                if (response.Value == null)
                {
                    throw new RequestFailedException(response.GetRawResponse());
                }
                return response;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                scope.Failed(e);
                throw;
            }
        }
```

The expected behavior is to use ToSerialString() when serializing the enum value for the request. The correct generated code should be:

``` .net
        public virtual Response RegenerateAdminKey(SearchServiceAdminKeyKind keyKind, SearchManagementRequestOptions searchManagementRequestOptions = default, CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
        {
            using DiagnosticScope scope = _adminKeysClientDiagnostics.CreateScope(&#34;SearchServiceResource.RegenerateAdminKey&#34;);
            scope.Start();
            try
            {
                RequestContext context = new RequestContext
                {
                    CancellationToken = cancellationToken
                };
                HttpMessage message = _adminKeysRestClient.CreateRegenerateAdminKeyRequest(Guid.Parse(Id.SubscriptionId), Id.ResourceGroupName, Id.Name, keyKind.ToSerialString(), default, context);
                Response result = Pipeline.ProcessMessage(message, context);
                Response response = Response.FromValue(SearchServiceAdminKeyResult.FromResponse(result), result);
                if (response.Value == null)
                {
                    throw new RequestFailedException(response.GetRawResponse());
                }
                return response;
            }
            catch (Exception e)
            {
                scope.Failed(e);
                throw;
            }
        }
```","state":"OPEN","user":{"login":"ArthurMa1978"},"labels":["Mgmt","CodeGen"],"created_at":"2026-03-20T16:48:11Z","updated_at":"2026-03-20T16:48:11Z"},{"number":57293,"title":"[Mgmt Generator] Missing WireV3Options for ManagedServiceIdentity serialization","body":"## Description

The mgmt generator does not emit `WireV3Options` for `ManagedServiceIdentity` serialization. This causes incorrect wire format for the `ManagedServiceIdentityType` value when `@armCommonTypesVersion` is v3, v5, or v6.

## Root Cause

The CommonTypes `ManagedServiceIdentityType` union has **different wire values per version**:

```typespec
union ManagedServiceIdentityType {
  &#34;None&#34;,
  &#34;SystemAssigned&#34;,
  &#34;UserAssigned&#34;,

  @added(Versions.v3) @removed(Versions.v4) @added(Versions.v5)
  &#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;,          // no space — v3, v5, v6

  @added(Versions.v4) @removed(Versions.v5)
  &#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;,         // with space — v4 only

  string,
}
```

The C# ARM SDK&#39;s `ManagedServiceIdentityType.SystemAssignedUserAssigned` has internal value `&#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;` (**v4 format, with space**). The ARM SDK&#39;s `ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs` supports a `&#34;|v3&#34;` format suffix to switch to the no-space wire format:

- `&#34;W|v3&#34;` → writes `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space, correct for v3/v5/v6)
- `&#34;W&#34;` → writes `ToString()` = `&#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;` (with space, correct for v4)

## How the old autorest generator detected this

The old autorest generator (`autorest.csharp`) uses `IsManagedServiceIdentityV3` in `SerializationBuilder.cs`:

```csharp
private static bool IsManagedServiceIdentityV3(InputType schema, CSharpType type)
{
    // 1. Check: C# type maps to the system ManagedServiceIdentity
    if (type is not { IsFrameworkType: false, Implementation: SystemObjectType systemObjectType }
        || systemObjectType.SystemType != typeof(ManagedServiceIdentity)
        || schema is not InputModelType objectSchema)
        return false;

    // 2. Check: the INPUT schema&#39;s &#34;type&#34; property enum contains &#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34; (no space)
    foreach (var m in objectSchema.GetSelfAndBaseModels())
        foreach (var property in m.Properties)
            if (property is { SerializedName: &#34;type&#34;, Type: InputEnumType choice }
                &amp;&amp; choice.Values.Any(c =&gt; c.Value.ToString() == &#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;))
                return true;

    return false;
}
```

**Key insight:** It does NOT check `@armCommonTypesVersion` directly. Instead it inspects the **input schema** (the original spec model before type mapping) and checks if the `type` property&#39;s enum contains the no-space value `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;`. This works because:
- v3/v5/v6 specs define `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space) → matches → `WireV3Options`
- v4 specs define `&#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;` (with space) → doesn&#39;t match → plain `WireOptions`

When matched, autorest uses `WireV3Options` / `WireV3Options` for both serialization and deserialization of `ManagedServiceIdentity`. See `JsonCodeWriterExtensions.cs:171` and `JsonSerializationMethodsBuilder.cs:445`.

## Version → WireOptions mapping

| `@armCommonTypesVersion` | Identity type wire value | Options needed |
|---|---|---|
| v3 | `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space) | `WireV3Options` (`&#34;W\|v3&#34;`) |
| v4 | `&#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;` (with space) | `WireOptions` (`&#34;W&#34;`) — current default |
| v5 | `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space) | `WireV3Options` (`&#34;W\|v3&#34;`) |
| v6 | `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space) | `WireV3Options` (`&#34;W\|v3&#34;`) |

## Repro

Already reproducible in the existing mgmt test project — no new TypeSpec needed.

The test project uses `@armCommonTypesVersion(v5)` and `Foo` has `...ManagedServiceIdentityV4Property`.

**Generated code** (`FooData.Serialization.cs` line 115):
```csharp
// Current (bug): uses plain options
((IJsonModel)Identity).Write(writer, options);
```

**Expected:**
```csharp
// Should use WireV3Options for v3/v5/v6
((IJsonModel)Identity).Write(writer, ModelSerializationExtensions.WireV3Options);
```

## Suggested Fix

The new mgmt emitter/generator should replicate autorest&#39;s detection logic:

1. When the output C# type is `ManagedServiceIdentity`, inspect the **input schema** (original spec model)
2. Check if the input model&#39;s `type` property has an enum value `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space)
3. If yes, generate `WireV3Options = new ModelReaderWriterOptions(&#34;W|v3&#34;)` in `ModelSerializationExtensions` and use it for serialization/deserialization of that property
4. If no (v4 format with space), use the default `WireOptions`

Alternatively, the emitter can check the `@armCommonTypesVersion` via `getArmCommonTypesVersion(program, entity)` (exported from `@azure-tools/typespec-azure-resource-manager`) and emit `WireV3Options` for v3/v5/v6.

## Impact

- Breaks wire compatibility: sends `&#34;SystemAssigned, UserAssigned&#34;` (with space) instead of `&#34;SystemAssigned,UserAssigned&#34;` (no space) for v3/v5/v6 specs
- Causes test recording mismatches (8 failures in Storage MPG migration PR #56896)

## Related

- Storage MPG migration PR: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/pull/56896
- Autorest detection: `autorest.csharp/src/AutoRest.CSharp/Common/Output/Builders/SerializationBuilder.cs` — `IsManagedServiceIdentityV3`
- ARM SDK v3 logic: `sdk/resourcemanager/Azure.ResourceManager/src/Common/Custom/Models/ManagedServiceIdentity.Serialization.cs`
","state":"OPEN","user":{"login":"live1206"},"labels":["Mgmt","CodeGen"],"comments":2,"created_at":"2026-03-20T10:25:46Z","updated_at":"2026-03-20T10:45:34Z"},{"number":57287,"title":"[Generator Bug] @@alternateType to armResourceType emits WriteObjectValue instead of WriteStringValue","body":"## Description

When `@@alternateType` maps a property to `Azure.Core.armResourceType` (C# `ResourceType`), the generator emits `WriteObjectValue(ResourceType, options)` for serialization. But `WriteObjectValue` has no case for `ResourceType` (which is a `readonly struct` wrapping a string), so it falls through to the `default` case and throws:

```
System.NotSupportedException: Not supported type Azure.Core.ResourceType
```

This also affects deserialization — the generator emits `ResourceType.DeserializeResourceType()` which doesn&#39;t exist as a public method.

## Affected Model (Storage MPG Migration)

- `StorageAccountNameAvailabilityContent` — spec has `type: &#34;Microsoft.Storage/storageAccounts&#34;` (constant string), mapped via:
```typespec
@@alternateType(StorageAccountCheckNameAvailabilityParameters.type, Azure.Core.armResourceType, &#34;csharp&#34;);
```

## Impact

This blocks **230 out of 287 tests** in the Storage SDK because nearly every test calls `CheckStorageAccountNameAvailability` during setup.

## Current Workaround

Custom `[CodeGenSerialization]` hooks for both directions:

```csharp
[CodeGenSerialization(nameof(ResourceType),
    DeserializationValueHook = nameof(DeserializeResourceType),
    SerializationValueHook = nameof(SerializeResourceType))]
public partial class StorageAccountNameAvailabilityContent
{
    private static void SerializeResourceType(Utf8JsonWriter writer, ResourceType resourceType)
    {
        writer.WriteStringValue(resourceType.ToString());
    }

    private static void DeserializeResourceType(JsonProperty property, ref ResourceType resourceType)
    {
        resourceType = new ResourceType(property.Value.GetString());
    }
}
```

**Note:** The `SerializationValueHook` requires regeneration to take effect. The generated file still has `WriteObjectValue` until regenerated.

## Comparison with Native Usage

When `armResourceType` is used as a **native property type** (not via `@@alternateType`), the generator correctly emits `WriteStringValue(ResourceType)`. The bug is specific to the `@@alternateType` code path.

**Works (native):** `testresourcetype.tsp`
```typespec
model ResourceTypeTestProperties {
  optionalResourceType?: Azure.Core.armResourceType;  // generates WriteStringValue ✓
}
```

**Broken (alternateType):** `client.tsp`
```typespec
@@alternateType(SomeModel.type, Azure.Core.armResourceType, &#34;csharp&#34;);  // generates WriteObjectValue ✗
```

## Related PR

- SDK PR: https://github.com/Azure/azure-sdk-for-net/pull/56896
